Getting started with sparklyr

Spark notes

R is a fantastic resource for data analysis and modeling, but it limits you to work on datasets that you can comfortably hold in the local RAM on your machine. Modern R offers the tidyverse which, as youve seen, is a really convenient syntax for transforming and visualising data.

Spark is a platform for cluster computing, which lets you spread data and computation over multiple machines in a cluster, opening up new opportunities to work on large data sets.

The sparklyr package gives us the best of both worlds! It lets us use convenient dplyr-like syntax to manipulate data, but converts those commands into code Spark can understand and dispatches them to a connected Spark cluster, so we can deal efficiently with big data problems.

A word of caution is in order though: sparklyr is very new, and features are rapidly evolving, so you must expect changes in how you work with the package in the short term.

Load up sparklyr and check out which Spark versions are

library("sparklyr")
spark_available_versions(show_minor = TRUE)
spark_install(version = "2.4.5")
spark_installed_versions()

Now connect to the Spark you just installed. To do this, we pass an argument master = "local", which lets sparklyr know that our local machine (i.e.your laptop) is being used as the master (or driver node) of a Spark cluster - in this case, just the master itself.

sc <- spark_connect(master = "local", version = "2.4.5")

Lets copy some data to Spark

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
avocados<- read_csv("data/avocado.csv")

avocados <- avocados %>%
  clean_names()
avocados_spark <- copy_to(sc, avocados)

If we had lost the reference to avocados locally, we can recreate it in this way

avocados_spark <- tbl(sc, "avocados")
src_tbls(sc)
[1] "avocados"
class(avocados_spark)
[1] "tbl_spark" "tbl_sql"   "tbl_lazy"  "tbl"

If we look inside this tbl_spark it doesnt actually contain any data, instead it points to a data source, i.e.Spark in this case. In this way, we avoid ever having to deal with all the data in Spark memory in the memory of the local machine. This is an example of lazy evaluation - dont actually acquire and deal with the data until the processing need arises.

Mutating to add features

avocados <- avocados %>%
  mutate(average_over_1.40 = average_price > 1.40)

  select(-c("date", "type", "region", "average_over_1.40")) %>%
  correlate(use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method = "pearson") %>%

  rplot()
